In &lt;user-880089.18122901112 ... @textnews.euro.net&gt;, Sander Tekelenburg wrote:

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Nobody seems to be sure yet what is up with Leopard's firewall, but it
&gt; doesn't look good: &lt; http://www.heise-security.co.uk/articles/98120 &gt;.
">

From the discussion of that article I've seen it is not as bad as all
that.  But this isn't a good start.  Still there are reasons to believe
that the author of that article (and me and loads of other people) have
failed to understand the network security model in Leopard.  I'm waiting
for the dust to settle and until I become more confident in my
understanding of new firewall.  I am a strong supporter of having both a
host based firewall and a perimeter firewall.  Given my utter bafflement
of what Apple is up to here, I'm looking relying on my perimeter firewall
to do this job at the moment.

Leopard really does introduce a number of security enhancements very deep
in the system.  And it may be that the new firewall design is set to
coordinate with that.

Alternatively, this could be that Apple sacrificed security just to get
Leopard out by the once-postponed release date and make sure that it &quot;Just
worked&quot; for most users.  I would be really, really pissed off if that
turns out to be the case, but I have to acknowledge that it remains a
possibility.

-j

